Taint helps to run workloads/pods on a node.
By default a Contraol Panel is tainted while Master is untained.
e.g In an untained cluster only the Control Panel is tainted to schedule critical workloads.

$ kubectl taint node master-node node-role.kubernetes.io/master:NoSchedule-
node/master-node untainted

Capture the Taint Results:
$ kubectl get nodes -o json | jq '.items[].spec.taints'
[
  {
    "effect": "NoSchedule",
    "key": "node-role.kubernetes.io/control-plane"
  }
]


Post taint: Master Node is also tainted to run workloads/pods if needed, generally Worker Nodes are tainted to help Master unstressful.
$ kubectl taint node master-node node-role.kubernetes.io/master:NoSchedule
node/master-node tainted

Capture the Taint Results:
$ kubectl get nodes -o json | jq '.items[].spec.taints'
[
  {
    "effect": "NoSchedule",
    "key": "node-role.kubernetes.io/master"
  },
  {
    "effect": "NoSchedule",
    "key": "node-role.kubernetes.io/control-plane"
  }
]
